{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538010"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:23:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16116"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16116"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.61,0.19,0.13,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8807"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63961"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8807"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16116"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49391"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"4981"},{"type":"tags","id":"7793"},{"type":"tags","id":"7845"},{"type":"tags","id":"11623"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"},{"type":"tags","id":"11814"},{"type":"tags","id":"12508"},{"type":"tags","id":"12803"},{"type":"tags","id":"13218"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32602"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45764"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63961"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about her migraines. She experiences three migraines per month and is interested in participating in research. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is invited to participate in a study investigating the relationship between dietary triggers and migraines. The study involves interviewing people who suffer from migraines about their dietary habits over the past year, comparing their responses to those without migraines.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following study designs is most likely to be affected by recall bias?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Randomised controlled trial","Case-control study","Cohort study","Cross-sectional study","Ecological study"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario describes a study design that is particularly susceptible to recall bias. \u003Cstrong\u003ECase-control studies\u003C/strong\u003E are most vulnerable to recall bias because cases (people with the condition) often search their memories more thoroughly than controls when asked about past exposures. In this scenario, migraine sufferers may be more likely to remember and report potential dietary triggers than those without migraines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandomised controlled trials\u003C/strong\u003E typically collect data prospectively and randomly allocate participants to interventions, making them less susceptible to recall bias. The controlled nature of data collection reduces the reliance on participant memory.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECohort studies\u003C/strong\u003E also typically collect data prospectively, following participants forward in time from exposure to outcome. This prospective design minimises recall bias as exposures are documented before outcomes occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECross-sectional studies\u003C/strong\u003E collect exposure and outcome data simultaneously at a single point in time. While they may involve some recall of past events, the impact of recall bias is generally less than in case-control studies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcological studies\u003C/strong\u003E use population-level data rather than individual-level data, and therefore are not directly affected by individual recall bias. Their limitations relate more to the ecological fallacy and inability to control for confounding at the individual level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecall bias is particularly problematic in case-control studies investigating potential risk factors for diseases, as cases may be more motivated to identify potential causes of their condition. This can lead to differential misclassification of exposures between cases and controls, potentially exaggerating or creating spurious associations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Recall bias occurs when there are systematic differences in how past events are remembered between groups.","Case-control studies are particularly susceptible to recall bias as cases may search their memories more thoroughly than controls.","Recall bias can lead to differential misclassification of exposures between cases and controls."],"references":["Coughlin SS. Recall bias in epidemiologic studies. J Clin Epidemiol. 1990;43(1):87-91. doi:10.1016/0895-4356(90)90060-3"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49391"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16116"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49391"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T20:04:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T20:05:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8807"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63961"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ud